## State with Objects

When state is an object or array, remember that you must create a **new object/array** when updating. Never mutate the existing one.

```jsx
const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: 'Alice', age: 25 });

// ❌ Wrong
user.age = 26;
setUser(user);

// ✅ Correct
setUser({ ...user, age: 26 });
```

The spread operator `...` creates a shallow copy. For arrays, use `[...array]` or `array.filter`, `array.map`, etc.

slides.codeSnippet:
const [items, setItems] = useState(['apple', 'banana']);

const addItem = (newItem) => {
  setItems(prevItems => [...prevItems, newItem]);
};

// Removing an item
const removeItem = (index) => {
  setItems(prevItems => prevItems.filter((_, i) => i !== index));
};
